145 void propagate_halide_function_call(
146 Expr adjoint,
147 const std::string &name, // called function name
148 const FunctionPtr &func_ptr, // pointer to halide function, is null if this is a call to buffer or param
149 const std::vector<Expr> &call_args, // call arguments
150 int value_index, // which element in the tuple
151 const Type &type // return type of the called function
152 );
153
154 // For each expression, we store the accumulated adjoints expression
155 map<const BaseExprNode *, Expr> expr_adjoints;
156 // For each function and each update, we store the accumulated adjoints func
157 map<FuncKey, Func> adjoint_funcs;
158 // Let variables and their mapping
159 map<string, Expr> let_var_mapping;
160 vector<string> let_variables;
161 // Bounds of functions
162 map<string, Box> func_bounds;
163 // Current function that scatters its adjoints to its dependencies
164 Func current_func;
165 // Current update of the function
166 int current_update_id;
167 // We compute the derivatives in several passes.
168 // Sometimes we don't want to propagate through Halide function calls
169 bool is_forward_overwrite_detection_phase;
170 bool is_self_referencing_phase;
171 // Is the current function update a non overwriting scan?
172 bool is_current_non_overwriting_scan;
173 // A temporary flag for checking the derivatives
174 // to self reference of a Halide function is 1 or not
175 // Used in forward overwrite detection phase
176 Tuple self_reference_adjoint = Tuple(Expr());
177 vector<vector<Expr>> self_reference_args;
178};
179
180void ReverseAccumulationVisitor::propagate_adjoints(
181 const Func &output,
182 const Func &adjoint,
183 const Region &output_bounds) {
184 // Topologically sort the functions
185 map<string, Function> env = find_transitive_calls(output.function());
186 vector<string> order =
187 realization_order({output.function()}, env).first;
188 vector<Func> funcs;
189 funcs.reserve(order.size());
190 // Internal::debug(0) << "Sorted Func list:\n";
191 // for (const auto &func_name : order) {
192 // Internal::debug(0) << " . " << func_name << "\n";
193 // }
194 for (const auto &func_name : order) {
195 funcs.emplace_back(env[func_name]);
196 }
197 internal_assert(!funcs.empty());
198
199 // If the derivatives depend on an in-place overwrite,
200 // and the self reference adjoint is not 0 or 1,
201 // throws an error to the users.
202 // For example:
203 //
204 // 1.
205 // f(x) = g(x)
206 // f(x) = f(x) * f(x)
207 // f'(x) depends on first f(x)
208 //
209 // 2.
210 // f(x) = 0
211 // f(x) = 2 * f(x) + g(r.x)
212 // g'(r.x) depends on intermediate f'(x)
213 //
214 // The following is fine because the self reference adjoint is 1:
215 // f(x) = f(x) + g(r.x)
216 // (when it's 1 all instances of f(x) have the same adjoint)
217 //
218 // The issue is that the self reference to f makes propagation to g
219 // using the wrong adjoints.
220 //
221 // The user should rewrite the above updates to the following:
222 //
223 // 1.
224 // f_(x, 0) = g(x)
225 // f_(x, 1) = f_(x, 0) * f_(x, 0)
226 // f(x) = f_(x, 1)
227 //
228 // 2.
229 // f_(x, 0) = 0
230 // f_(x, r.x + 1) = 2 * f_(x, r.x) + g(r.x)
231 // f(x) = f_(x, r.x.max() + 1)
232 //
233 // We can do the rewrite for the users automatically, but it requires
234 // generating the indirect reference f_, making scheduling these
235 // functions extremely difficult.
236 is_forward_overwrite_detection_phase = true;
237 set<FuncKey> non_overwriting_scans;
238 for (int func_id = 0; func_id < (int)funcs.size(); func_id++) {
239 const Func &func = funcs[func_id];
240 current_func = func;
241 // Precompute the left hand side intervals for each update
242 // We use this to determine if there's overlaps between the updates
243 vector<Box> boxes;
244 boxes.reserve(func.num_update_definitions());
245 for (int update_id = 0;
246 update_id < func.num_update_definitions(); update_id++) {
247 const vector<Expr> &args = func.update_args(update_id);
248 vector<Interval> intervals;
249 intervals.reserve(args.size());
250 for (int arg_id = 0; arg_id < (int)args.size(); arg_id++) {
251 Scope<Interval> scope;
252 ReductionDomain rdom = extract_rdom(args[arg_id]);
253 if (rdom.defined()) {
254 const vector<ReductionVariable> &rvars = rdom.domain();
255 for (const auto &r : rvars) {
256 Expr r_max = simplify(r.min + r.extent + 1);
257 scope.push(r.var, Interval(r.min, r_max));
258 }
259 }
260 Interval interval = bounds_of_expr_in_scope(args[arg_id], scope);
261 intervals.push_back(interval);
262 }
263 boxes.emplace_back(intervals);
264 }
265 for (int update_id = 0;
266 update_id < func.num_update_definitions(); update_id++) {
267 // We check for two criteria:
268 // 1. We check if the derivatives
269 // depend on previous update, and if that particular
270 // value has been overwritten.
271 // 2. For updates of f with reduction variables,
272 // unless the derivatives to self reference is 1 or 0,
273 // we make sure overwritten f' is not used by others.
274 // We conservatively detect this by distinguish two cases:
275 // a. If f' is always never being overwritten for all instances of
276 // the reduction variables
277 // b. Or if f' is never used by others except itself.
278 //
279 // A few examples:
280 //
281 // f(x) = f(x) + g(r.x) // good, the self update derivative is 1
282 //
283 // f(x) = 2 * f(x) // good, although the self update derivative is 2,
284 // there's no reduction variables
285 //
286 // f(x) = 2 * f(x) + g(r.x) // bad, f'(x) will be used for updating
287 // g(r.x) but will be overwritten
288 //
289 // f(x) = f(x) * f(x) // bad, derivative of f(x) depends on previous value
290 // which has been overwritten
291 //
292 // f(x, 0) = ...
293 // f(x, 1) = f(x, 0) * f(x, 0) // good, although the derivative depends on
294 // // previous value, the updates do not overlap
295 //
296 // f(x, r.x + 1) = 2 * f(x, r.x) + g(r.x) // good,
297 // // f' is never overwritten
298 //
299 // f(x, y) = g(x)
300 // f(x, r.x + 1) = f(x, r.x) * f(x, r.x); // bad, the derivatives
301 // depend on previous updates
302 //
303 // f(x, y, 0) = g(x)
304 // f(x, r.x + 1, 1) = f(x, r.x, 0) * f(x, r.x, 0); // good
305 //
306 // f(x, r.x + 1, r.y + 1) = 2 * f(x, r.x, r.y) + g(r.x) // good
307 //
308 // f(x, r.x + 1, r.x + r.y + 1) = 2 * f(x, r.x, r.y) + g(r.x) // bad
309
310 vector<Expr> zeros;
311 Tuple rhs_tuple = func.values();
312 zeros.reserve(rhs_tuple.size());
313 for (int i = 0; i < (int)rhs_tuple.size(); i++) {
314 zeros.push_back(make_zero(rhs_tuple[i].type()));
315 }
316 self_reference_adjoint = Tuple(zeros);
317 self_reference_args.clear();
318 // Checking 1. here:
319 // Take the derivative at expression level, the results are
320 // stored in expr_adjoints
321 vector<Expr> expr_list;
322 Tuple update_tuple = func.update_values(update_id);
323 vector<const BaseExprNode *> output_exprs;
324 const vector<Expr> &update_tuple_vector = update_tuple.as_vector();
325 for (const auto &expr : update_tuple_vector) {
326 vector<Expr> value_expr_list = sort_expressions(expr);
327 expr_list.insert(expr_list.end(),
328 value_expr_list.begin(), value_expr_list.end());
329 output_exprs.push_back((const BaseExprNode *)expr_list.back().get());
330 }
331
332 // TODO: replace let_var_mapping with Scope
333 // Gather let variables
334 let_var_mapping.clear();
335 let_variables.clear();
336 for (auto it = expr_list.begin(); it != expr_list.end(); it++) {
337 Expr expr = *it;
338 if (expr.get()->node_type == IRNodeType::Let) {
339 const Let *op = expr.as<Let>();
340 // Assume Let variables are unique
341 internal_assert(let_var_mapping.find(op->name) == let_var_mapping.end());
342 let_var_mapping[op->name] = op->value;
343 let_variables.push_back(op->name);
344 }
345 }
346
347 // Set the output adjoint to 1
348 // We're not really propagating adjoints, just checking if there's
349 // self references
350 for (int i = 0; i < (int)output_exprs.size(); i++) {
351 expr_adjoints[output_exprs[i]] = 1.f;
352 }
353
354 // Traverse the expressions in reverse order
355 for (auto it = expr_list.rbegin(); it != expr_list.rend(); it++) {
356 if (it->type().is_handle()) {
357 // Ignore pointer types
358 continue;
359 }
360 it->accept(this);
361 }
362
363 auto error = [&]() {
364 user_error << "Can't take the gradients of " << func.name() << ", which depend on intermediate values. "
365 << "Use a scan (which saves intermediate results) instead.";
366 };
367
368 // For each adjoint expression depositing to a function or image,
369 // check if it references to the function
370 bool adjoints_used_by_others = false;
371 for (const auto &it : expr_adjoints) {
372 Expr target_expr(it.first);
373 bool is_target_func_or_buffer = false;
374 const Call *call_op = target_expr.as<Call>();
375 if (call_op != nullptr) {
376 is_target_func_or_buffer =
377 call_op->call_type == Call::Image ||
378 call_op->call_type == Call::Halide;
379 }
380 Expr expr = it.second;
381 if (is_target_func_or_buffer &&
382 is_calling_function(func.name(), expr, let_var_mapping)) {
383 // Self reference might not be bad.
384 // If we carefully avoid overwriting intermediate values,
385 // we can still backprop.
386 // First we check for the pure definition.
387 // If the pure definition depends on any functions or buffers,
388 // there is no hope since we will overwrite something
389 Tuple rhs_tuple = func.values();
390 for (int tuple_id = 0; tuple_id < (int)rhs_tuple.size();
391 tuple_id++) {
392 if (is_calling_function(rhs_tuple[tuple_id], let_var_mapping)) {
393 error();
394 }
395 }
396 // Now we check all previous updates, see if the left hand
397 // side arguments overlap.
398 Box current_box = boxes[update_id];
399 for (int prev_update_id = 0; prev_update_id < update_id;
400 prev_update_id++) {
401 // Gather two boxes from current update and previous update
402 Box prev_box = boxes[prev_update_id];
403 internal_assert(current_box.size() == prev_box.size());
404 // If any of the boxes overlap, we need to throw an error
405 if (boxes_overlap(current_box, prev_box)) {
406 error();
407 }
408 }
409 }
410
411 if (is_target_func_or_buffer && call_op->name != func.name()) {
412 adjoints_used_by_others = true;
413 }
414 }
415 expr_adjoints.clear();
416
417 // Checking 2. here:
418 bool all_zero_or_one_self_adjoint = true;
419 for (int i = 0; i < (int)self_reference_adjoint.size(); i++) {
420 if (!is_const(self_reference_adjoint[i], 0) &&
421 !is_const(self_reference_adjoint[i], 1)) {
422 all_zero_or_one_self_adjoint = false;
423 break;
424 }
425 }
426 bool has_reduction_var = !func.rvars(update_id).empty();
427 if (!all_zero_or_one_self_adjoint && has_reduction_var) {
428 // a. is there any instance of reduction variable such that
429 // the self reference update overwrites itself?
430 // Or, equivalently, for all possible values of the reduction
431 // variables, does the self reference update always
432 // reads from/writes to different locations?
433 // First we determine the ranges of RDoms for
434 // and_condition_over_domain
435 Scope<Interval> varying;
436 // Loop over lhs & rhs to grab a reduction domain
437 ReductionDomain r;
438 const vector<Expr> &update_args = func.update_args(update_id);
439 for (const Expr &expr : update_args) {
440 r = extract_rdom(expr);
441 if (r.defined()) {
442 break;
443 }
444 }
445 if (!r.defined()) {
446 for (int tuple_id = 0; tuple_id < (int)update_tuple.size();
447 tuple_id++) {
448 r = extract_rdom(update_tuple[tuple_id]);
449 if (r.defined()) {
450 break;
451 }
452 }
453 }
454 internal_assert(r.defined());
455 // Go over all self reference call arguments
456 bool is_not_overwriting = true;
457 for (const vector<Expr> &self_ref_args : self_reference_args) {
458 internal_assert(self_ref_args.size() == update_args.size());
459 Expr not_overwriting_cond = const_false();
460 for (int arg_id = 0; arg_id < (int)self_ref_args.size(); arg_id++) {
461 // Are the read from/write to arguments always different?
462 not_overwriting_cond = simplify(not_overwriting_cond ||
463 (self_ref_args[arg_id] != update_args[arg_id]));
464 }
465 not_overwriting_cond = and_condition_over_domain(
466 not_overwriting_cond, varying);
467 // Needs to be true for all self reference
468 is_not_overwriting = is_not_overwriting &&
469 can_prove(not_overwriting_cond);
470 }
471
472 // b. Even if the derivative is overwritten, as long as
473 // we don't use it in this update we are good.
474 // Otherwise we throw an error
475 if (!is_not_overwriting && adjoints_used_by_others) {
476 error();
477 }
478
479 if (is_not_overwriting) {
480 // This is a non overwriting scan, let's remember it
481 non_overwriting_scans.insert(FuncKey{func.name(), update_id});
482 }
483 }
484 }
485 }
486 is_forward_overwrite_detection_phase = false;
487
488 // Bounds inference
489 Box output_box;
490 for (const auto &p : output_bounds) {
491 // Convert from min,extent to min,max
492 output_box.push_back(Interval(p.min, p.min + p.extent));
493 }
494 func_bounds = inference_bounds(output, output_box);
495 for (const auto &it : func_bounds) {
496 const Box &bounds = it.second;
497 for (int d = 0; d < (int)bounds.size(); d++) {
498 user_assert(bounds[d].is_bounded()) << "Access to function or buffer " << it.first << " at dimension " << d << " is not bounded. "
499 << "We can only differentiate bounded accesses.\n";
500 }
501 }
502
503 // Create a stub for each function and each update to accumulate adjoints.
504 for (int func_id = 0; func_id < (int)funcs.size(); func_id++) {
505 const Func &func = funcs[func_id];
506 for (int update_id = -1; update_id < func.num_update_definitions(); update_id++) {
507 Func adjoint_func(func.name() + "_" + std::to_string(update_id + 1) + "_d_def__");
508 bool is_final_output = func_id == (int)funcs.size() - 1 &&
509 update_id == func.num_update_definitions() - 1;
510 vector<Var> args = func.args();
511 for (auto &arg : args) {
512 if (arg.is_implicit()) {
513 // Replace implicit variables with non implicit ones
514 arg = Var();
515 }
516 }
517 if (is_final_output) {
518 adjoint_func(args) = adjoint(args);
519 } else {
520 // Initialize to 0
521 if (func.values().size() == 1) {
522 adjoint_func(args) = make_zero(func.values()[0].type());
523 } else {
524 vector<Expr> init(func.values().size());
525 for (int i = 0; i < (int)init.size(); i++) {
526 init[i] = make_zero(func.values()[i].type());
527 }
528 adjoint_func(args) = Tuple(init);
529 }
530 }
531 FuncKey func_key{func.name(), update_id};
532 internal_assert(adjoint_funcs.find(func_key) == adjoint_funcs.end());
533 adjoint_funcs[func_key] = adjoint_func;
534 }
535 }
536 // Also create stubs for buffers referenced by the functions
537 map<string, BufferInfo> called_buffers_or_param;
538 for (int func_id = 0; func_id < (int)funcs.size(); func_id++) {
539 const Func &func = funcs[func_id];
540 map<string, BufferInfo> buffers = find_buffer_param_calls(func);
541 called_buffers_or_param.insert(buffers.begin(), buffers.end());
542 }
543 for (const auto &it : called_buffers_or_param) {
544 // Replace all the dots in the function names to make it legal.
545 Func adjoint_func(replace_all(it.first, ".", "_") + "_d__");
546 vector<Var> args(it.second.dimension);
547 adjoint_func(args) = make_zero(it.second.type);
548 FuncKey func_key{it.first, -1};
549 if (adjoint_funcs.find(func_key) != adjoint_funcs.end()) {
550 user_error << "Naming conflict between buffer/parameters and function:" << it.first << "\n";
551 }
552 adjoint_funcs[func_key] = adjoint_func;
553 }
554
555 // Traverse functions from producers to consumers for reverse accumulation
556 for (int func_id = funcs.size() - 1; func_id >= 0; func_id--) {
557 const Func &func = funcs[func_id];
558 current_func = func;
559
560 FuncKey func_key{func.name(), func.num_update_definitions() - 1};
561 // Traverse from the last update to first
562 for (int update_id = func.num_update_definitions() - 1;
563 update_id >= -1; update_id--) {
564 current_update_id = update_id;
565 FuncKey func_key{func.name(), update_id};
566 Func adjoint_func = adjoint_funcs[func_key];
567 internal_assert(func_bounds.find(func.name()) != func_bounds.end());
568 // The propagation of adjoints to self reference goes to
569 // current update instead of previous if it's a non overwriting scan
570 is_current_non_overwriting_scan = false;
571 if (update_id >= 0) {
572 auto it = non_overwriting_scans.find(func_key);
573 if (it != non_overwriting_scans.end()) {
574 is_current_non_overwriting_scan = true;
575 }
576 }
577
578 // Initialize the next adjoint function by
579 // propagating the adjoints to next update
580 // Example:
581 // f(x) = ...
582 // f(1) = ... <- we're here
583 // We have an adjoint for f(1) defined over the whole support of f
584 // Now we want to initialize for the f(x) update
585 // Need to propagate back to all x while masking 1
586 // x -> next_args
587 // 1 -> update_args
588 auto mask_previous_update = [&]() {
589 FuncKey prev_func_key{func.name(), update_id - 1};
590 Func &prev_adjoint_func = adjoint_funcs[prev_func_key];
591 vector<Var> prev_args = prev_adjoint_func.args();
592 vector<Expr> update_args = func.update_args(update_id);
593 // Replace implicit variables
594 for (auto &arg : update_args) {
595 set<string> implicit_variables =
596 find_implicit_variables(arg);
597 for (const auto &var : implicit_variables) {
598 arg = substitute(var, prev_args[Var::implicit_index(var)], arg);
599 }
600 }
601 // Check if prev_args are the same as update_args
602 // If they are the same simply set everything to zero
603 bool is_noop = true;
604 for (int i = 0; i < (int)prev_args.size(); i++) {
605 const Variable *update_var = update_args[i].as<Variable>();
606 if (update_var == nullptr || prev_args[i].name() != update_var->name) {
607 is_noop = false;
608 }
609 }
610 prev_adjoint_func = Func(prev_adjoint_func.name());
611 if (!is_noop) {
612 // f'(x) = adjoint
613 prev_adjoint_func(prev_args) =
614 adjoint_funcs[func_key](prev_args);
615 if (func.values().size() == 1) {
616 Type type = func.values()[0].type();
617 prev_adjoint_func(update_args) = make_zero(type);
618 } else {
619 vector<Expr> init(func.values().size());
620 for (int i = 0; i < (int)init.size(); i++) {
621 init[i] = make_zero(func.values()[i].type());
622 }
623 prev_adjoint_func(update_args) = Tuple(init);
624 }
625 } else {
626 if (func.values().size() == 1) {
627 Type type = func.values()[0].type();
628 prev_adjoint_func(prev_args) = make_zero(type);
629 } else {
630 vector<Expr> init(func.values().size());
631 for (int i = 0; i < (int)init.size(); i++) {
632 init[i] = make_zero(func.values()[i].type());
633 }
634 prev_adjoint_func(prev_args) = Tuple(init);
635 }
636 }
637 };
638 if (update_id >= 0 && !is_current_non_overwriting_scan) {
639 // Delay the masking if we're keeping track of intermediate values.
640 // Since in this case we are propagating to current update,
641 // instead of previous update.
642 mask_previous_update();
643 }
644
645 // Now we want to propagate the derivatives at expression level.
646 // We topologically sort the expressions for each value in the tuple.
647 vector<Expr> expr_list;
648 Tuple rhs_tuple =
649 update_id < 0 ? func.values() : func.update_values(update_id);
650 vector<const BaseExprNode *> output_exprs;
651 const vector<Expr> &rhs_tuple_vector = rhs_tuple.as_vector();
652 for (const auto &expr : rhs_tuple_vector) {
653 vector<Expr> value_expr_list = sort_expressions(expr);
654 expr_list.insert(
655 expr_list.end(), value_expr_list.begin(), value_expr_list.end());
656 output_exprs.push_back((const BaseExprNode *)expr_list.back().get());
657 }
658
659 // TODO: replace let_var_mapping with Scope
660 // Gather let variables
661 let_var_mapping.clear();
662 let_variables.clear();
663 for (auto it = expr_list.begin(); it != expr_list.end(); it++) {
664 Expr expr = *it;
665 if (expr.get()->node_type == IRNodeType::Let) {
666 const Let *op = expr.as<Let>();
667 // Assume Let variables are unique
668 internal_assert(let_var_mapping.find(op->name) == let_var_mapping.end());
669 let_var_mapping[op->name] = op->value;
670 let_variables.push_back(op->name);
671 }
672 }
673
674 // Retrieve previously propagated adjoint for the Func,
675 // apply it to expression adjoints.
676 // f(x) = g(x)
677 // d_g(x) = d_f(x) * df/dg
678 vector<Expr> update_args;
679 if (update_id >= 0) {
680 update_args = func.update_args(update_id);
681 } else {
682 update_args.reserve(func.args().size());
683 Func adjoint_func = adjoint_funcs[func_key];
684 for (const auto &var : adjoint_func.args()) {
685 update_args.push_back(var);
686 }
687 }
688
689 // We propagate in two phases, the first phase only propagates
690 // to self references, the second phase propagates to the rest.
691 { // First phase
692 is_self_referencing_phase = true;
693 expr_adjoints.clear();
694 if (output_exprs.size() == 1) {
695 expr_adjoints[output_exprs[0]] =
696 (adjoint_funcs[func_key])(update_args);
697 } else {
698 for (int i = 0; i < (int)output_exprs.size(); i++) {
699 expr_adjoints[output_exprs[i]] =
700 (adjoint_funcs[func_key])(update_args)[i];
701 }
702 }
703
704 // Traverse the expressions in reverse order
705 for (auto it = expr_list.rbegin(); it != expr_list.rend(); it++) {
706 if (it->type().is_handle()) {
707 // Ignore pointer types
708 continue;
709 }
710 // Propagate adjoints
711 it->accept(this);
712 }
713 }
714 if (is_current_non_overwriting_scan) {
715 // Now, if we detect a non-overwriting scan operation,
716 // the update of adjoints goes to the current function.
717 // We let the previous adjoint the same as the current one
718
719 FuncKey prev_func_key{func_key.first, func_key.second - 1};
720 // Recreate a new adjoint for previous update
721 Func prev_adjoint;
722 vector<Expr> args;
723 args.reserve(adjoint_func.args().size());
724 for (const auto &arg : adjoint_func.args()) {
725 args.push_back(arg);
726 }
727 vector<Expr> calls;
728 calls.reserve(rhs_tuple.size());
729 for (int i = 0; i < (int)rhs_tuple.size(); i++) {
730 calls.push_back(Call::make(
731 adjoint_funcs[func_key].function(), args, i));
732 }
733 prev_adjoint(args) = Tuple(calls);
734 adjoint_funcs[prev_func_key] = prev_adjoint;
735 mask_previous_update();
736 }
737 { // Second phase
738 is_self_referencing_phase = false;
739 expr_adjoints.clear();
740 for (int i = 0; i < (int)output_exprs.size(); i++) {
741 expr_adjoints[output_exprs[i]] =
742 Call::make(adjoint_funcs[func_key].function(),
743 update_args, i);
744 }
745
746 int count = 0;
747 // Traverse the expressions in reverse order
748 for (auto it = expr_list.rbegin(); it != expr_list.rend(); it++) {
749 if (it->type().is_handle()) {
750 // Ignore pointer types
751 continue;
752 }
753 // Propagate adjoints
754 it->accept(this);
755 count++;
756 }
757 }
758 }
759 }
760}
761
762void ReverseAccumulationVisitor::accumulate(const Expr &stub, Expr adjoint) {
763 const BaseExprNode *stub_ptr = (const BaseExprNode *)stub.get();
764
765 // Trick to avoid NaN in select() clauses:
766 // select(c, x, 0) * y -> select(c, x * y, 0)
767 // x * select(c, y, 0) -> select(c, x * y, 0)
768 // select(c, x, 0) / y -> select(c, x / y, 0)
769 if (adjoint.as<Mul>() != nullptr) {
770 const Mul *mul_op = adjoint.as<Mul>();
771 auto mul_select_with_zero = [&](const Expr &sel, const Expr &other) {
772 const Select *sel_op = sel.as<Select>();
773 if (is_const_zero(sel_op->true_value)) {
774 return select(sel_op->condition,
775 sel_op->true_value, sel_op->false_value * other);
776 }
777 if (is_const_zero(sel_op->false_value)) {
778 return select(sel_op->condition,
779 sel_op->true_value * other, sel_op->false_value);
780 }
781 return sel * other;
782 };
783 if (mul_op->a.as<Select>() != nullptr) {
784 adjoint = mul_select_with_zero(mul_op->a, mul_op->b);
785 } else if (mul_op->b.as<Select>() != nullptr) {
786 adjoint = mul_select_with_zero(mul_op->b, mul_op->a);
787 }
788 }
789 if (adjoint.as<Div>() != nullptr) {
790 const Div *div_op = adjoint.as<Div>();
791 auto div_select_with_zero = [&](const Expr &sel, const Expr &other) {
792 const Select *sel_op = sel.as<Select>();
793 if (is_const_zero(sel_op->true_value)) {
794 return select(sel_op->condition,
795 sel_op->true_value, sel_op->false_value / other);
796 }
797 if (is_const_zero(sel_op->false_value)) {
798 return select(sel_op->condition,
799 sel_op->true_value / other, sel_op->false_value);
800 }
801 return sel * other;
802 };
803 if (div_op->a.as<Select>() != nullptr) {
804 adjoint = div_select_with_zero(div_op->a, div_op->b);
805 }
806 }
807
808 if (expr_adjoints.find(stub_ptr) == expr_adjoints.end()) {
809 expr_adjoints[stub_ptr] = adjoint;
810 } else {
811 expr_adjoints[stub_ptr] = expr_adjoints[stub_ptr] + adjoint;
812 }
813}

831void ReverseAccumulationVisitor::visit(const Cast *op) {
832 internal_assert(expr_adjoints.find(op) != expr_adjoints.end());
833 Expr adjoint = expr_adjoints[op];
834
835 // d/dx cast(x) = 1.f if op->type is float otherwise 0
836 if (op->type.is_float()) {
837 accumulate(op->value, cast(op->value.type(), adjoint));

839 accumulate(op->value, make_zero(op->value.type()));
840 }

843void ReverseAccumulationVisitor::visit(const Variable *op) {
844 internal_assert(expr_adjoints.find(op) != expr_adjoints.end());
845 Expr adjoint = expr_adjoints[op];
846
847 if (op->param.defined()) {
848 // This is a reference to a Parameter, propagate to the corresponding buffer
849 propagate_halide_function_call(adjoint, op->param.name(), FunctionPtr(), {}, 0, op->type);
850 return;
851 }
852
853 // If the variable is a let variable, accumulates adjoints into the content
854 auto it = let_var_mapping.find(op->name);
855 if (it != let_var_mapping.end()) {
856 accumulate(it->second, Let::make(op->name, it->second, adjoint));
857 }
858}

890void ReverseAccumulationVisitor::visit(const Div *op) {
891 internal_assert(expr_adjoints.find(op) != expr_adjoints.end());
892 Expr adjoint = expr_adjoints[op];
893
894 // Trick to avoid NaN in select() clauses: if adjoint is a select with an 0,
895 // multiply into it
896 if (adjoint.as<Select>() != nullptr) {
897 const Select *sel_op = adjoint.as<Select>();
898 if (is_const_zero(sel_op->true_value)) {
899 // d/da a / b = 1 / b
900 accumulate(op->a, select(sel_op->condition,
901 sel_op->true_value, sel_op->false_value / op->b));
902 // d/db a * b = - a / b^2
903 accumulate(op->b, select(sel_op->condition,
904 sel_op->true_value, -sel_op->false_value * op->a / (op->b * op->b)));
905 return;
906 }
907 if (is_const_zero(sel_op->false_value)) {
908 // d/da a / b = 1 / b
909 accumulate(op->a, select(sel_op->condition,
910 sel_op->true_value / op->b, sel_op->false_value));
911 // d/db a * b = - a / b^2
912 accumulate(op->b, select(sel_op->condition,
913 -sel_op->true_value * op->a / (op->b * op->b), sel_op->false_value));
914 return;
915 }
916 }
917
918 // d/da a / b = 1 / b
919 accumulate(op->a, adjoint / op->b);
920 // d/db a / b = - a / b^2
921 accumulate(op->b, -adjoint * op->a / (op->b * op->b));
922}
923
924void ReverseAccumulationVisitor::visit(const Mod *op) {
925 internal_assert(expr_adjoints.find(op) != expr_adjoints.end());
926 Expr adjoint = expr_adjoints[op];
927
928 // a % b = a - trunc(a/b) * b
929 // d/da = 1
930 accumulate(op->a, adjoint);
931 // d/db = -trunc(a/b)
932 accumulate(op->b, -adjoint * trunc(op->a / op->b));
933}

942 // d/db min(a, b) = b <= a ? 1 : 0
943 accumulate(op->b,

1058void ReverseAccumulationVisitor::visit(const Call *op) {
1059 internal_assert(expr_adjoints.find(op) != expr_adjoints.end());
1060 Expr adjoint = expr_adjoints[op];
1061 if (op->is_extern()) {
1062 // Math functions
1063 if (is_float_extern(op->name, "exp")) {
1064 // d/dx exp(x) = exp(x)
1065 accumulate(op->args[0], adjoint * exp(op->args[0]));
1066 } else if (is_float_extern(op->name, "log")) {
1067 // d/dx log(x) = 1 / x
1068 accumulate(op->args[0], adjoint / op->args[0]);
1069 } else if (is_float_extern(op->name, "sin")) {
1070 // d/dx sin(x) = cos(x)
1071 accumulate(op->args[0], adjoint * cos(op->args[0]));
1072 } else if (is_float_extern(op->name, "asin")) {
1073 // d/dx asin(x) = 1 / sqrt(1 - x^2)
1074 Expr one = make_one(op->type);
1075 accumulate(op->args[0], adjoint / sqrt(one - op->args[0] * op->args[0]));
1076 } else if (is_float_extern(op->name, "cos")) {
1077 // d/dx cos(x) = -sin(x)
1078 accumulate(op->args[0], -adjoint * sin(op->args[0]));
1079 } else if (is_float_extern(op->name, "acos")) {
1080 // d/dx acos(x) = - 1 / sqrt(1 - x^2)
1081 Expr one = make_one(op->type);
1082 accumulate(op->args[0], -adjoint / sqrt(one - op->args[0] * op->args[0]));
1083 } else if (is_float_extern(op->name, "tan")) {
1084 // d/dx tan(x) = 1 / cos(x)^2
1085 Expr c = cos(op->args[0]);
1086 accumulate(op->args[0], adjoint / (c * c));
1087 } else if (is_float_extern(op->name, "atan")) {
1088 // d/dx atan(x) = 1 / (1 + x^2)
1089 Expr one = make_one(op->type);
1090 accumulate(op->args[0], adjoint / (one + op->args[0] * op->args[0]));
1091 } else if (is_float_extern(op->name, "atan2")) {
1092 Expr x2y2 = op->args[0] * op->args[0] + op->args[1] * op->args[1];
1093 // d/dy atan2(y, x) = x / (x^2 + y^2)
1094 accumulate(op->args[0], adjoint * (op->args[1] / x2y2));
1095 // d/dx atan2(y, x) = -y / (x^2 + y^2)
1096 accumulate(op->args[1], adjoint * (-op->args[0] / x2y2));
1097 } else if (is_float_extern(op->name, "sinh")) {
1098 // d/dx sinh(x) = cosh(x)
1099 accumulate(op->args[0], adjoint * cosh(op->args[0]));
1100 } else if (is_float_extern(op->name, "asinh")) {
1101 // d/dx asin(x) = 1 / sqrt(1 + x^2)
1102 Expr one = make_one(op->type);
1103 accumulate(op->args[0], adjoint / sqrt(one + op->args[0] * op->args[0]));
1104 } else if (is_float_extern(op->name, "cosh")) {
1105 // d/dx cosh(x) = sinh(x)
1106 accumulate(op->args[0], adjoint * sinh(op->args[0]));
1107 } else if (is_float_extern(op->name, "acosh")) {
1108 // d/dx acosh(x) = 1 / (sqrt(x - 1) sqrt(x + 1)))
1109 Expr one = make_one(op->type);
1110 accumulate(op->args[0],
1111 adjoint / (sqrt(op->args[0] - one) * sqrt(op->args[0] + one)));
1112 } else if (is_float_extern(op->name, "tanh")) {
1113 // d/dx tanh(x) = 1 / cosh(x)^2
1114 Expr c = cosh(op->args[0]);
1115 accumulate(op->args[0], adjoint / (c * c));
1116 } else if (is_float_extern(op->name, "atanh")) {
1117 // d/dx atanh(x) = 1 / (1 - x^2)
1118 Expr one = make_one(op->type);
1119 accumulate(op->args[0], adjoint / (one - op->args[0] * op->args[0]));
1120 } else if (is_float_extern(op->name, "ceil")) {
1121 // TODO: d/dx = dirac(n) for n in Z ...
1122 accumulate(op->args[0], make_zero(op->type));
1123 } else if (is_float_extern(op->name, "floor")) {
1124 // TODO: d/dx = dirac(n) for n in Z ...
1125 accumulate(op->args[0], make_zero(op->type));
1126 } else if (is_float_extern(op->name, "round")) {
1127 accumulate(op->args[0], make_zero(op->type));
1128 } else if (is_float_extern(op->name, "trunc")) {
1129 accumulate(op->args[0], make_zero(op->type));
1130 } else if (is_float_extern(op->name, "sqrt")) {
1131 Expr half = make_const(op->type, 0.5);
1132 accumulate(op->args[0], adjoint * (half / sqrt(op->args[0])));
1133 } else if (is_float_extern(op->name, "pow")) {
1134 Expr one = make_one(op->type);
1135 accumulate(op->args[0],
1136 adjoint * op->args[1] * pow(op->args[0], op->args[1] - one));
1137 accumulate(op->args[1],
1138 adjoint * pow(op->args[0], op->args[1]) * log(op->args[0]));
1139 } else if (is_float_extern(op->name, "fast_inverse")) {
1140 // d/dx 1/x = -1/x^2
1141 Expr inv_x = fast_inverse(op->args[0]);
1142 accumulate(op->args[0], -adjoint * inv_x * inv_x);
1143 } else if (is_float_extern(op->name, "fast_inverse_sqrt")) {
1144 // d/dx x^(-0.5) = -0.5*x^(-1.5)
1145 Expr inv_sqrt_x = fast_inverse_sqrt(op->args[0]);
1146 Expr neg_half = make_const(op->type, -0.5);
1147 accumulate(op->args[0],
1148 neg_half * adjoint * inv_sqrt_x * inv_sqrt_x * inv_sqrt_x);
1149 } else if (op->name == "halide_print") {
1150 for (const auto &arg : op->args) {
1151 accumulate(arg, make_zero(op->type));
1152 }
1153 } else {
1154 internal_error << "The derivative of " << op->name << " is not implemented.";
1155 }
1156 } else if (op->is_intrinsic()) {
1157 if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::abs)) {
1158 accumulate(op->args[0],
1159 adjoint * select(op->args[0] > 0,
1160 make_one(op->type), make_const(op->type, -1.0)));
1161 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::lerp)) {
1162 // z = x * (1 - w) + y * w
1163 // dz/dx = 1 - w
1164 // dz/dy = w
1165 // dz/dw = y - x
1166 accumulate(op->args[0], adjoint * (make_one(op->type) - op->args[2]));
1167 accumulate(op->args[1], adjoint * op->args[2]);
1168 accumulate(op->args[2], adjoint * (op->args[1] - op->args[0]));
1169 } else if (Call::as_tag(op)) {
1170 accumulate(op->args[0], adjoint);
1171 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::return_second)) {
1172 accumulate(op->args[0], make_const(op->type, 0.0));
1173 accumulate(op->args[1], adjoint);
1174 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::undef)) {
1175 // do nothing
1176 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::reinterpret) ||
1177 op->is_intrinsic(Call::bitwise_and) ||
1178 op->is_intrinsic(Call::bitwise_not) ||
1179 op->is_intrinsic(Call::bitwise_or) ||
1180 op->is_intrinsic(Call::bitwise_xor) ||
1181 op->is_intrinsic(Call::shift_right) ||
1182 op->is_intrinsic(Call::shift_left)) {
1183 // bit manipulations -- these have zero derivatives.
1184 for (const auto &arg : op->args) {
1185 accumulate(arg, make_zero(op->type));
1186 }
1187 } else {
1188 user_warning << "Dropping gradients at call to " << op->name << "\n";
1189 for (const auto &arg : op->args) {
1190 accumulate(arg, make_zero(op->type));
1191 }
1192 }
1193 } else if (op->call_type == Call::Halide ||
1194 op->call_type == Call::Image) { // Halide function call or Halid buffer
1195 propagate_halide_function_call(adjoint, op->name, op->func, op->args, op->value_index, op->type);
1196 } else {
1197 // TODO: let user provide derivatives for external functions
1198 internal_error << "Unknown call type of operation: " << op->name << "\n";
1199 }
1200}
1201
1202void ReverseAccumulationVisitor::propagate_halide_function_call(
1203 Expr adjoint, const std::string &name, const FunctionPtr &func_ptr,
1204 const std::vector<Expr> &call_args, int value_index, const Type &type) {
1205 if (!type.is_float()) {
1206 // If the function call does not return continuous output,
1207 // don't propagate to the function.
1208 return;
1209 }
1210 // Add Let expressions
1211 adjoint = add_let_expression(adjoint, let_var_mapping, let_variables);
1212 vector<Expr> lhs = call_args;
1213 for (int i = 0; i < (int)lhs.size(); i++) {
1214 lhs[i] = add_let_expression(lhs[i], let_var_mapping, let_variables);
1215 }
1216 Expr adjoint_before_canonicalize = adjoint;
1217 vector<Expr> lhs_before_canonicalize = lhs;
1218
1219 if (is_forward_overwrite_detection_phase) {
1220 // Don't need to propagate through function in this phase, we're just
1221 // checking local derivatives
1222 // However, we'll accumulate the derivatives to self reference
1223 // for checking if the self update is harmful for gradients
1224 if (func_ptr.same_as(current_func.function().get_contents())) {
1225 self_reference_adjoint[value_index] =
1226 simplify(self_reference_adjoint[value_index] + adjoint);
1227 vector<Expr> args = call_args;
1228 for (int i = 0; i < (int)args.size(); i++) {
1229 args[i] = add_let_expression(args[i], let_var_mapping, let_variables);
1230 }
1231 self_reference_args.push_back(args);
1232 }
1233 return;
1234 }
1235 if (is_self_referencing_phase) {
1236 // We want to make sure we propagate to the self reference first.
1237 // In this phase only self reference is propagated
1238 if (!func_ptr.same_as(current_func.function().get_contents())) {
1239 return;
1240 }
1241 } else {
1242 // In the other phase we ignore the self reference
1243 if (func_ptr.same_as(current_func.function().get_contents())) {
1244 return;
1245 }
1246 }
1247
1248 // We create different functions for the initial condition and each update
1249 // When update i uses value from update i-1, we accumulate the
1250 // adjoints to update i-1
1251 // If target is the current function itself, send to previous update
1252 // e.g. f(x) = ...
1253 // f(x) = f(x) + 1
1254 // For the one with non-commutative-associative reductions
1255 // e.g. f(x, ver) = ...
1256 // f(x, 0) = ...
1257 // f(x, r.x + 1) = f(x, r.x) * f(x, r.x) + g(r.x)
1258 // We propagate the whole r.x to the current update.
1259 // In addition, we propagate the first one d_f(x, 0) to the previous update,
1260 // by setting all reduction variables to their min() values.
1261 // Because only f(x, 0) comes from the last update, and
1262 // the rest belongs to the current update.
1263 // The above case will be handled by the caller, here we just
1264 // propagate to current update.
1265 // TODO: make the comments clearer and clean up the code
1266 FuncKey func_key;
1267 if (func_ptr.defined()) {
1268 Function func(func_ptr);
1269 func_key = func.name() != current_func.name() ? FuncKey{func.name(), func.updates().size() - 1} : FuncKey{func.name(), current_update_id - 1};
1270 if (is_current_non_overwriting_scan && is_self_referencing_phase) {
1271 func_key = FuncKey{func.name(), current_update_id};
1272 }
1273 } else {
1274 func_key = FuncKey{name, -1};
1275 }
1276 internal_assert(adjoint_funcs.find(func_key) != adjoint_funcs.end());
1277 Func &func_to_update = adjoint_funcs[func_key];
1278 internal_assert(func_to_update.dimensions() == (int)lhs.size());
1279
1280 bool debug_flag = false;
1281 adjoint = simplify(common_subexpression_elimination(adjoint));
1282
1283 if (debug_flag) {
1284 debug(0) << "current_func:" << current_func.name() << "\n";
1285 debug(0) << "Scattering to " << name << "\n";
1286 debug(0) << "lhs is:";
1287 for (const auto &arg : lhs) {
1288 debug(0) << " " << arg;
1289 }
1290 debug(0) << "\n";
1291 debug(0) << "adjoint is:" << simplify(adjoint) << "\n";
1292 }
1293
1294 // Gather argument & bounds information
1295 // current_args are the pure variables
1296 // current_update_args are the actual updates at left hand side
1297 Func current_adjoint_func =
1298 adjoint_funcs[FuncKey{current_func.name(), current_update_id}];
1299 vector<Var> current_args = current_adjoint_func.args();
1300 const Box &current_bounds = func_bounds[current_func.name()];
1301
1302 // Replace implicit variables
1303 for (auto &arg : lhs) {
1304 set<string> implicit_variables = find_implicit_variables(arg);
1305 for (const auto &var : implicit_variables) {
1306 arg = substitute(var, current_args[Var::implicit_index(var)], arg);
1307 }
1308 }
1309 {
1310 set<string> implicit_variables =
1311 find_implicit_variables(adjoint);
1312 for (const auto &var : implicit_variables) {
1313 adjoint = substitute(
1314 var, current_args[Var::implicit_index(var)], adjoint);
1315 }
1316 }
1317
1318 // We want to do this:
1319 // func_to_update(call_args) += adjoint(current_update_args);
1320 // But call_args can be invalid lhs, need to canonicalize.
1321 // We canonicalize by first trying to substitute with pure variables.
1322 // If that fails we will replace variables on lhs with RDoms
1323 // (general scattering).
1324
1325 // We try canonicalize the left hand side arguments (call_args)
1326 // so that it's always x, y, z, ...
1327 //
1328 // Given:
1329 // g(x, y, z) = f(x, y-1, z+1)
1330 // we get an invalid update:
1331 // f'(x, y - 1, z + 1) += g'(x, y, z)
1332 // Goal: rewrite to
1333 // ==> f'(x, y, z) += g'(x, y+1, z-1)
1334 // (below we would call g and g' the "current function" and
1335 // we call f and d_f the "function to update")
1336 //
1337 // We do this by set up a new set of variables new_args
1338 // new_args contains a set of variable u0, u1, u2, ...
1339 // For each left hand side of the update (x, y - 1, z + 1 here),
1340 // we set up the equations u0 = x, u1 = y - 1, u2 = z + 1.
1341 // Then we solve for x, y, z and get x = u0, y = u1 + 1, z = u2 - 1
1342 // We get f'(u0, u1, u2) += g'(u0, u1 + 1, u2 - 1)
1343 // We then substitute the original variable names back to get
1344 // f'(x, y, z) += g'(x, x + 1, z - 1)
1345 //
1346 // Note that g' would correctly returns 0 outside g's boundary,
1347 // therefore we do not need to impose bounds on g'.
1348 // However, consider the case where f'(...) += g'(...) * h(...):
1349 // we need to clamp h's arguments such that it never goes out of g's domain,
1350 // otherwise we may get unwanted out-of-bound buffer access.
1351 //
1352 // Currently we don't want to mess with system solving.
1353 // Therefore we gather all arguments that contains multiple pure variables,
1354 // and invalidate all of them.
1355 // Inter-dependencies like:
1356 // g(x, y) = f(x * y, x + y)
1357 // can't be simplified.
1358 // In principle this can be inverted by solving a system of equations.
1359 // In this case we replace x and y with reduction variables that loop
1360 // through g's bounds
1361 // i.e.
1362 // f'(r.x * r.y, r.x + r.y) += g'(r.x, r.y)
1363
1364 // Prepare a set of new substitution variables for func_to_update
1365 vector<Var> new_args;
1366 new_args.reserve(func_to_update.dimensions());
1367 for (int arg_id = 0; arg_id < (int)func_to_update.dimensions(); arg_id++) {
1368 new_args.emplace_back(unique_name("u" + std::to_string(arg_id)));
1369 }
1370
1371 // Loop over the left hand side of the update, construct equations
1372 // and invert them.
1373 vector<bool> canonicalized(lhs.size(), false);
1374 set<string> canonicalized_vars;
1375 map<string, Var> lhs_substitute_map;
1376 for (int arg_id = 0; arg_id < (int)lhs.size(); arg_id++) {
1377 // Gather all pure variables at call_args[arg_id],
1378 // substitute them with new_args
1379 // For now only support single pure variable
1380 vector<int> variable_ids =
1381 gather_variables(lhs[arg_id], current_args);
1382 if (variable_ids.size() != 1) {
1383 continue;
1384 }
1385
1386 int variable_id = variable_ids[0];
1387 const string &variable = current_args[variable_id].name();
1388 bool solved;
1389 Expr result_rhs;
1390 std::tie(solved, result_rhs) =
1391 solve_inverse(new_args[arg_id] == lhs[arg_id],
1392 new_args[arg_id].name(),
1393 variable);
1394 if (!solved) {
1395 continue;
1396 }
1397
1398 // Substitute all access to variable to clamped version
1399 Expr clamped_variable = clamp(likely(current_args[variable_id]),
1400 current_bounds[variable_id].min,
1401 current_bounds[variable_id].max);
1402 adjoint = substitute_rdom_predicate(variable, clamped_variable, adjoint);
1403 // However we don't want to clamp the access to adjoint function (we need
1404 // it to return 0 outside of its bounds). We replace the corresponding
1405 // clamped argument back with the pure variable. It is safe to do
1406 // so because pure variable in Halide's update function can only be appeared
1407 // unadorned in the same position.
1408 adjoint = substitute_call_arg_with_pure_arg(current_adjoint_func,
1409 variable_id,
1410 adjoint);
1411
1412 // Replace pure variable with the reverse.
1413 // Make sure to also substitute predicates.
1414 adjoint = substitute_rdom_predicate(variable, result_rhs, adjoint);
1415
1416 // Since we successfully invert, the left hand side becomes new_args
1417 lhs[arg_id] = new_args[arg_id];
1418 // Record that we successfully invert, for those we fail
1419 // we need to perform general scattering.
1420 canonicalized[arg_id] = true;
1421 canonicalized_vars.insert(variable);
1422 lhs_substitute_map[variable] = new_args[arg_id];
1423 }
1424
1425 // Consider the following case:
1426 // f(x, y) = ...
1427 // k(n) = f(g(n), n)
1428 // When we update d_f, the second n would be replaced by y.
1429 // We need to make sure we also update the call argument to g.
1430 // Adjoint is automatically handled in the loop above.
1431 for (int i = 0; i < (int)lhs.size(); i++) {
1432 for (const auto &it : lhs_substitute_map) {
1433 lhs[i] = substitute(it.first, it.second, lhs[i]);
1434 }
1435 }
1436
1437 // Sometimes the canonicalization above fails.
1438 // We replace the pure variables inside lhs with RDoms for general scattering
1439 Region bounds;
1440 bounds.reserve(current_args.size());
1441 for (int arg_id = 0; arg_id < (int)current_args.size(); arg_id++) {
1442 const Interval &interval = current_bounds[arg_id];
1443 bounds.emplace_back(interval.min, interval.max - interval.min + 1);
1444 }
1445 RDom r_bounds(bounds);
1446 for (int lhs_id = 0; lhs_id < (int)lhs.size(); lhs_id++) {
1447 if (!canonicalized[lhs_id]) {
1448 Expr lhs_arg = lhs[lhs_id];
1449 vector<string> adjoint_args = current_adjoint_func.function().args();
1450 vector<int> variable_ids = gather_variables(lhs_arg, adjoint_args);
1451 // For each variable found in lhs_arg, find the corresponding
1452 // bound (by looping through all variables) and substitute
1453 // with the bound reduction variable.
1454 for (int var_id = 0; var_id < (int)variable_ids.size(); var_id++) {
1455 for (int arg_id = 0; arg_id < (int)current_args.size(); arg_id++) {
1456 const string &variable = adjoint_args[variable_ids[var_id]];
1457 if (current_args[arg_id].name() == variable &&
1458 canonicalized_vars.find(
1459 current_args[arg_id].name()) ==
1460 canonicalized_vars.end()) {
1461 lhs[lhs_id] = substitute(variable,
1462 r_bounds[arg_id],
1463 lhs[lhs_id]);
1464 adjoint = substitute(variable, r_bounds[arg_id], adjoint);
1465 break;
1466 }
1467 }
1468 }
1469 }
1470 }
1471
1472 // For each free variable on the rhs, replace it with current bounds
1473 // e.g. we have in forward pass f(x, y) = g(x)
1474 // then we would have g'(x) += f'(x, y) by now
1475 // now we need to replace y with a reduction variable over f's bound
1476 // x is automatically excluded since it's currently
1477 // replaced by the new substitution variable e.g. u_0
1478
1479 // First gather all free variables
1480 Region bounds_subset;
1481 vector<int> arg_id_to_substitute;
1482 bounds_subset.reserve(current_args.size());
1483 arg_id_to_substitute.reserve(current_args.size());
1484 for (int arg_id = 0; arg_id < (int)current_args.size(); arg_id++) {
1485 if (expr_uses_var(adjoint, current_args[arg_id].name())) {
1486 const Interval &interval = current_bounds[arg_id];
1487 bounds_subset.emplace_back(
1488 interval.min, interval.max - interval.min + 1);
1489 arg_id_to_substitute.push_back(arg_id);
1490 }
1491 }
1492
1493 // Create a new RDom to loop over all free variables
1494 if (!arg_id_to_substitute.empty()) {
1495 RDom r(bounds_subset);
1496 for (int i = 0; i < (int)arg_id_to_substitute.size(); i++) {
1497 int arg_id = arg_id_to_substitute[i];
1498 adjoint = substitute(current_args[arg_id].name(), r[i], adjoint);
1499 }
1500 }
1501
1502 // Simplify expressions
1503 adjoint = simplify(common_subexpression_elimination(adjoint));
1504 for (int i = 0; i < (int)lhs.size(); i++) {
1505 lhs[i] = simplify(common_subexpression_elimination(lhs[i]));
1506 }
1507
1508 vector<Var> func_to_update_args = func_to_update.args();
1509
1510 // General scattering simplification rules:
1511 // For each expression in lhs,
1512 // check if it is an expression of a single (associative & commutative)
1513 // rvar and spans the same interval of the function's bound
1514 // if so we can rewrite it back to pure variables
1515 // e.g.
1516 // f(r.x) = g(r.x)
1517 // => f(x) = g(x)
1518 //
1519 // Another common pattern is the reverse of downsampling
1520 // if we see s * r.x + r.y and r.y has min == 0 and extent == s
1521 // we simplify them to x and replace all occurrences of r.x by x/4
1522 // e.g.
1523 // f(4 * r.x + r.y) = g(r.x) + h(4 * r.x + r.y)
1524 // => f(x) = g(x/4) + h(x)
1525 Expr new_adjoint = func_to_update.values().size() == 1 ? (func_to_update(lhs) + adjoint) : (func_to_update(lhs)[value_index] + adjoint);
1526 vector<Expr> new_adjoint_tuple(func_to_update.values().size(), Expr(0.f));
1527 new_adjoint_tuple[value_index] = new_adjoint;
1528 AssociativeOp associative_op = prove_associativity(
1529 func_to_update.name(), lhs, new_adjoint_tuple);
1530 if (associative_op.associative() && associative_op.commutative()) {
1531 for (int i = 0; i < (int)lhs.size(); i++) {
1532 Expr lhs_arg = substitute_in_all_lets(lhs[i]);
1533 const Variable *var = lhs_arg.as<Variable>();
1534 const Add *add = lhs_arg.as<Add>();
1535 // f(r.x) = ... && r is associative
1536 // => f(x) = ...
1537 if (var != nullptr && var->reduction_domain.defined() &&
1538 var->reduction_domain.split_predicate().empty()) {
1539 ReductionDomain rdom = var->reduction_domain;
1540 int rvar_id = -1;
1541 for (int rid = 0; rid < (int)rdom.domain().size(); rid++) {
1542 if (rdom.domain()[rid].var == var->name) {
1543 rvar_id = rid;
1544 break;
1545 }
1546 }
1547 internal_assert(rvar_id != -1);
1548 ReductionVariable rvar = rdom.domain()[rvar_id];
1549 // Check if the min/max of the rvariable is equal to
1550 // the target function
1551 const Box &target_bounds = func_bounds[name];
1552 Interval t_interval = target_bounds[i];
1553 t_interval.min = simplify(t_interval.min);
1554 t_interval.max = simplify(t_interval.max);
1555 Interval r_interval(simplify(rvar.min),
1556 simplify(rvar.min + rvar.extent - 1));
1557 if (can_prove(r_interval.min <= t_interval.min &&
1558 r_interval.max >= t_interval.max)) {
1559 lhs[i] = func_to_update_args[i];
1560 Expr clamped_arg = clamp(func_to_update_args[i],
1561 r_interval.min, r_interval.max);
1562 // Replace other occurrence of rvar in lhs
1563 for (int j = 0; j < (int)lhs.size(); j++) {
1564 if (j != i) {
1565 lhs[j] = simplify(substitute(
1566 rvar.var, clamped_arg, lhs[j]));
1567 }
1568 }
1569 // Take care of boundary condition
1570 Expr in_bound = func_to_update_args[i] >= r_interval.min &&
1571 func_to_update_args[i] <= r_interval.max;
1572 adjoint = select(in_bound,
1573 simplify(substitute(rvar.var, clamped_arg, adjoint)),
1574 make_zero(adjoint.type()));
1575 }
1576 // f(4 * r.x + r.y) = g(r.x) + h(4 * r.x + r.y)
1577 // => f(x) = g(x/4) + h(x)
1578 } else if (add != nullptr &&
1579 ((add->a.as<Mul>() != nullptr &&
1580 add->b.as<Variable>() != nullptr) ||
1581 (add->a.as<Variable>() != nullptr &&
1582 add->b.as<Mul>() != nullptr))) {
1583 // Find pattern s * r.x + r.y where r.y.min == 0 && r.y.extent == s
1584 Expr a = add->a, b = add->b;
1585 if (add->b.as<Mul>() != nullptr) {
1586 // swap so that b is always the Variable
1587 internal_assert(add->a.as<Variable>() != nullptr);
1588 std::swap(a, b);
1589 }
1590 const Mul *mul = a.as<Mul>();
1591 const Variable *b_var = b.as<Variable>();
1592 internal_assert(mul != nullptr && b_var != nullptr);
1593 Expr mul_a = mul->a, mul_b = mul->b;
1594 if (mul_a.as<Variable>() != nullptr &&
1595 mul_a.as<Variable>()->reduction_domain.defined()) {
1596 std::swap(mul_a, mul_b);
1597 }
1598 const Variable *mul_b_var = mul_b.as<Variable>();
1599 if (mul_b_var == nullptr || !mul_b_var->reduction_domain.defined()) {
1600 continue;
1601 }
1602 ReductionDomain b_rdom = b_var->reduction_domain;
1603 if (!b_rdom.defined()) {
1604 continue;
1605 }
1606
1607 int rvar_id = -1;
1608 for (int rid = 0; rid < (int)b_rdom.domain().size(); rid++) {
1609 if (b_rdom.domain()[rid].var == b_var->name) {
1610 rvar_id = rid;
1611 break;
1612 }
1613 }
1614 internal_assert(rvar_id != -1);
1615 ReductionVariable rvar = b_rdom.domain()[rvar_id];
1616 if (!equal(rvar.min, Expr(0)) || !equal(rvar.extent, mul_a)) {
1617 continue;
1618 }
1619
1620 ReductionDomain mul_b_rdom = mul_b_var->reduction_domain;
1621 int mulb_rvar_id = -1;
1622 for (int rid = 0; rid < (int)mul_b_rdom.domain().size(); rid++) {
1623 if (mul_b_rdom.domain()[rid].var == mul_b_var->name) {
1624 mulb_rvar_id = rid;
1625 break;
1626 }
1627 }
1628 internal_assert(mulb_rvar_id != -1);
1629 ReductionVariable mulb_rvar = b_rdom.domain()[mulb_rvar_id];
1630
1631 // Check if the min/max of the s * r.x + r.y is equal to
1632 // the target function
1633 const Box &target_bounds = func_bounds[name];
1634 Interval t_interval = target_bounds[i];
1635 t_interval.min = simplify(t_interval.min);
1636 t_interval.max = simplify(t_interval.max);
1637 Interval r_interval(simplify(mul_a * mulb_rvar.min),
1638 simplify(mul_a * mulb_rvar.extent - 1));
1639
1640 if (can_prove(r_interval.min <= t_interval.min &&
1641 r_interval.max >= t_interval.max)) {
1642 // We've finally made sure that the expression has the form we want
1643 // Now replace everything
1644 // replace s * r.x + r.y with x
1645 lhs[i] = func_to_update_args[i];
1646 adjoint = substitute(lhs_arg,
1647 func_to_update_args[i],
1648 substitute_in_all_lets(adjoint));
1649 // replace r.x with x / s
1650 adjoint = substitute(mul_b, func_to_update_args[i] / mul_a, adjoint);
1651 adjoint = simplify(adjoint);
1652 }
1653 }
1654 }
1655 }
1656
1657 // We can only have one RDom for each update.
1658 // Therefore we have to merge RDoms on both lhs and rhs
1659 // To make use of better locality we preserve partial order
1660 map<string, ReductionVariableInfo> rvar_maps =
1661 gather_rvariables(adjoint);
1662 for (const auto &lhs_arg : lhs) {
1663 map<string, ReductionVariableInfo> maps =
1664 gather_rvariables(lhs_arg);
1665 rvar_maps.insert(maps.begin(), maps.end());
1666 }
1667 // Original set of reduction variables
1668 map<string, ReductionVariableInfo> org_rvar_maps =
1669 gather_rvariables(adjoint_before_canonicalize);
1670 for (const auto &lhs_arg : lhs_before_canonicalize) {
1671 map<string, ReductionVariableInfo> maps =
1672 gather_rvariables(lhs_arg);
1673 org_rvar_maps.insert(maps.begin(), maps.end());
1674 }
1675 // If the update is non-commutative or non-associative, we need to flip the
1676 // original set of reduction variable
1677 if (is_current_non_overwriting_scan) {
1678 // For each lhs
1679 for (auto &lhs_arg : lhs) {
1680 // For each original rvar
1681 for (const auto &it : org_rvar_maps) {
1682 RVar r(it.second.domain, it.second.index);
1683 Expr max = simplify(it.second.min + it.second.extent - 1);
1684 // Replace the reduction with the flipped version
1685 lhs_arg = substitute(it.first, max - r, lhs_arg);
1686 }
1687 }
1688 // For adjoint
1689 // For each original rvar
1690 for (const auto &it : org_rvar_maps) {
1691 RVar r(it.second.domain, it.second.index);
1692 Expr max = simplify(it.second.min + it.second.extent - 1);
1693 // Replace the reduction with the flipped version
1694 adjoint = substitute(it.first, max - r, adjoint);
1695 }
1696 }
1697
1698 // Order: newly introduced rvar -> original rvar
1699 vector<ReductionVariableInfo> new_rvar_vec, old_rvar_vec;
1700 for (const auto &it : rvar_maps) {
1701 if (org_rvar_maps.find(it.first) == org_rvar_maps.end()) {
1702 new_rvar_vec.push_back(it.second);
1703 } else {
1704 old_rvar_vec.push_back(it.second);
1705 }
1706 }
1707
1708 // Sort by index & domain
1709 auto cmp_rv = [](const ReductionVariableInfo &rv0,
1710 const ReductionVariableInfo &rv1) {
1711 ReductionDomain::Compare cmp;
1712 if (cmp(rv0.domain, rv1.domain)) {
1713 return true;
1714 } else {
1715 return rv0.index < rv1.index;
1716 }
1717 };
1718 std::sort(new_rvar_vec.begin(), new_rvar_vec.end(), cmp_rv);
1719 std::sort(old_rvar_vec.begin(), old_rvar_vec.end(), cmp_rv);
1720 // Flatten to an array
1721 vector<string> var_names;
1722 Region merged_bounds;
1723 for (const auto &it : new_rvar_vec) {
1724 var_names.push_back(it.name);
1725 merged_bounds.emplace_back(it.min, it.extent);
1726 }
1727 for (const auto &it : old_rvar_vec) {
1728 var_names.push_back(it.name);
1729 merged_bounds.emplace_back(it.min, it.extent);
1730 }
1731 // Produce final merged RDom
1732 RDom merged_r;
1733 if (!merged_bounds.empty()) {
1734 merged_r = RDom(merged_bounds);
1735 // Transfer the predicate from old RDoms to merged RDom
1736 // Gather the set of RDoms
1737 set<ReductionDomain, ReductionDomain::Compare> rdoms;
1738 for (const auto &it : rvar_maps) {
1739 rdoms.insert(it.second.domain);
1740 }
1741 Expr rdom_predicate = Internal::UIntImm::make(UInt(1), 1);
1742 for (const auto &rdom : rdoms) {
1743 rdom_predicate = simplify(rdom_predicate && rdom.predicate());
1744 }
1745 // Reference to new RDom
1746 for (int rid = 0; rid < merged_r.dimensions(); rid++) {
1747 adjoint = substitute(var_names[rid], merged_r[rid], adjoint);
1748 for (auto &lhs_arg : lhs) {
1749 lhs_arg = substitute(var_names[rid], merged_r[rid], lhs_arg);
1750 }
1751 rdom_predicate = substitute(
1752 var_names[rid], merged_r[rid], rdom_predicate);
1753 }
1754 if (!is_const(rdom_predicate)) {
1755 for (int arg_id = 0; arg_id < (int)func_to_update_args.size(); arg_id++) {
1756 // Substitute new_args back to original variables
1757 rdom_predicate = substitute(new_args[arg_id].name(),
1758 func_to_update_args[arg_id], rdom_predicate);
1759 }
1760 merged_r.where(rdom_predicate);
1761 }
1762 }
1763
1764 // Substitute new_args back to original variables
1765 for (int arg_id = 0; arg_id < (int)func_to_update_args.size(); arg_id++) {
1766 for (auto &lhs_arg : lhs) {
1767 lhs_arg = substitute(new_args[arg_id].name(),
1768 func_to_update_args[arg_id], lhs_arg);
1769 }
1770 adjoint = substitute_rdom_predicate(
1771 new_args[arg_id].name(), func_to_update_args[arg_id], adjoint);
1772 }
1773
1774 // Simplify expressions
1775 adjoint = simplify(common_subexpression_elimination(adjoint));
1776 for (int i = 0; i < (int)lhs.size(); i++) {
1777 lhs[i] = simplify(common_subexpression_elimination(lhs[i]));
1778 }
1779
1780 if (debug_flag) {
1781 debug(0) << "func_to_update.name():" << func_to_update.name() << "\n";
1782 debug(0) << "lhs after canonicalization:";
1783 for (const auto &arg : lhs) {
1784 debug(0) << " " << arg;
1785 }
1786 debug(0) << "\n";
1787 debug(0) << "adjoint after canonicalization:" << simplify(adjoint) << "\n";
1788 }
1789
1790 // Finally we update the function definitions, possibly merge with previous updates
1791 auto can_merge = [&](Func &func_to_update,
1792 const vector<Expr> &lhs) -> bool {
1793 if (func_to_update.num_update_definitions() == 0) {
1794 // If lhs are not pure variables we can't merge to pure definition
1795 for (int i = 0; i < (int)lhs.size(); i++) {
1796 if (!equal(lhs[i], func_to_update.args()[i])) {
1797 return false;
1798 }
1799 }
1800 ReductionDomain rdom = extract_rdom(adjoint);
1801 // If there are rdoms in adjoint we can't merge
1802 return !rdom.defined();
1803 }
1804 int update_id = func_to_update.num_update_definitions() - 1;
1805 vector<Expr> prev_lhs =
1806 func_to_update.update_args(update_id);
1807 internal_assert(prev_lhs.size() == lhs.size());
1808 // If previous update has different left hand side, don't merge
1809 for (int i = 0; i < (int)prev_lhs.size(); i++) {
1810 if (!equal(lhs[i], prev_lhs[i])) {
1811 return false;
1812 }
1813 }
1814 // If previous update has a different set of reduction variables,
1815 // don't merge
1816 const vector<ReductionVariable> &rvars =
1817 func_to_update.update(update_id).get_schedule().rvars();
1818 if (!merged_r.defined()) {
1819 return rvars.empty();
1820 }
1821 if ((int)rvars.size() != merged_r.dimensions()) {
1822 return false;
1823 }
1824
1825 for (int i = 0; i < (int)rvars.size(); i++) {
1826 if (!equal(rvars[i].min, merged_r[i].min())) {
1827 return false;
1828 }
1829 if (!equal(rvars[i].extent, merged_r[i].extent())) {
1830 return false;
1831 }
1832 }
1833 return true;
1834 };
1835 if (is_self_referencing_phase) {
1836 // If this is a self reference call, the relation is = instead of +=
1837 // For example, consider this:
1838 // f(x) = g(x)
1839 // f(k(r.x)) += h(r.x)
1840 // Multiple k(r.x) may correspond to the same index,
1841 // but they are overwritten in the reduction loop.
1842 // Therefore we should also overwrite their derivatives
1843 // by using = instead of +=
1844 if (!can_merge(func_to_update, lhs)) {
1845 if (func_to_update.values().size() == 1) {
1846 func_to_update(lhs) = adjoint;
1847 } else {
1848 func_to_update(lhs)[value_index] = adjoint;
1849 }
1850 } else {
1851 Definition &def = func_to_update.num_update_definitions() == 0 ? func_to_update.function().definition() : func_to_update.function().update(func_to_update.num_update_definitions() - 1);
1852 vector<Expr> &values = def.values();
1853 ReductionDomain rdom;
1854 for (const auto &val : values) {
1855 rdom = extract_rdom(val);
1856 if (rdom.defined()) {
1857 break;
1858 }
1859 }
1860 if (rdom.defined()) {
1861 internal_assert(func_to_update.num_update_definitions() > 0);
1862 // Make sure we're using the same set of reduction variables
1863 for (int i = 0; i < merged_r.dimensions(); i++) {
1864 adjoint = substitute(merged_r[i].name(), RVar(rdom, i), adjoint);
1865 }
1866 }
1867
1868 if (values.size() == 1) {
1869 values[0] = adjoint;
1870 } else {
1871 values[value_index] = adjoint;
1872 }
1873 }
1874 return;
1875 }
1876
1877 if (!can_merge(func_to_update, lhs)) {
1878 if (func_to_update.values().size() == 1) {
1879 func_to_update(lhs) += adjoint;
1880 } else {
1881 func_to_update(lhs)[value_index] += adjoint;
1882 }
1883 } else {
1884 Definition &def = func_to_update.num_update_definitions() == 0 ? func_to_update.function().definition() : func_to_update.function().update(func_to_update.num_update_definitions() - 1);
1885 vector<Expr> &values = def.values();
1886 ReductionDomain rdom;
1887 for (const auto &val : values) {
1888 rdom = extract_rdom(val);
1889 if (rdom.defined()) {
1890 break;
1891 }
1892 }
1893 if (rdom.defined()) {
1894 internal_assert(func_to_update.num_update_definitions() > 0);
1895 // Make sure we're using the same set of reduction variables
1896 for (int i = 0; i < merged_r.dimensions(); i++) {
1897 adjoint = substitute(merged_r[i].name(), RVar(rdom, i), adjoint);
1898 }
1899 }
1900
1901 if (values.size() == 1) {
1902 values[0] = simplify(values[0] + adjoint);
1903 } else {
1904 const Add *add = values[value_index].as<Add>();
1905 if (add != nullptr &&
1906 add->b.as<Call>() != nullptr &&
1907 add->b.as<Call>()->is_intrinsic(Call::undef)) {
1908 // Sometimes the expression is an undef for the case of a tuple.
1909 // Make sure we don't include the undefs
1910 values[value_index] = simplify(add->a + adjoint);
1911 } else {
1912 values[value_index] =
1913 simplify(values[value_index] + adjoint);
1914 }
1915 }
1916 }
1917}

1948
1949Derivative propagate_adjoints(const Func &output,
1950 const Func &adjoint,
1951 const Region &output_bounds) {
1952 user_assert(output.dimensions() == adjoint.dimensions())
1953 << "output dimensions and adjoint dimensions must match\n";
1954 user_assert((int)output_bounds.size() == adjoint.dimensions())
1955 << "output_bounds and adjoint dimensions must match\n";
1956
1957 Internal::ReverseAccumulationVisitor visitor;
1958 visitor.propagate_adjoints(output, adjoint, output_bounds);
1959 // Since the return value of get_adjoint_funcs() is a temporary,
1960 // we should *not* use std::move.
1961 return Derivative{visitor.get_adjoint_funcs()};
1962}
1963
1964Derivative propagate_adjoints(const Func &output,
1965 const Buffer<float> &adjoint) {
1966 user_assert(output.dimensions() == adjoint.dimensions());
1967 Region bounds;
1968 for (int dim = 0; dim < adjoint.dimensions(); dim++) {
1969 bounds.emplace_back(adjoint.min(dim), adjoint.min(dim) + adjoint.extent(dim) - 1);
1970 }
1971 Func adjoint_func = BoundaryConditions::constant_exterior(adjoint, 0.f);
1972 return propagate_adjoints(output, adjoint_func, bounds);
1973}
1974
1975Derivative propagate_adjoints(const Func &output) {
1976 Func adjoint("adjoint");
1977 adjoint(output.args()) = Internal::make_one(output.value().type());
1978 Region output_bounds;
1979 output_bounds.reserve(output.dimensions());
1980 for (int i = 0; i < output.dimensions(); i++) {
1981 output_bounds.push_back({0, 0});
1982 }
1983 return propagate_adjoints(output, adjoint, output_bounds);
1984}
